### Description

This is a feature request for first-class template-level control-flow blocks that render only on a specific platform:

```html
@server {
  <!-- This block is rendered only during SSR/prerendering. -->
}

@browser {
  <!-- This block is rendered only in the browser. -->
}
```

The goal is to make SSR/browser-only rendering explicit in Angular templates and make this behavior hydration-aware.

Today this can be approximated with isPlatformBrowser, isPlatformServer, custom structural directives, or component-level guards. However, those solutions are verbose, easy to implement inconsistently, and do not provide a clear framework-level contract for hydration behavior.

Angular already has template control-flow syntax such as `@if`, `@for`, `@switch`, and `@defer`. SSR apps often need a similarly clear way to express platform-specific template branches.

#### Common use cases:

```html
@server {
  <app-static-product-card [product]="product" />
}

@browser {
  <app-interactive-product-card [product]="product" />
}
```

```html
@server {
  <app-seo-friendly-table [rows]="rows" />
}

@browser {
  <app-virtual-scroll-table [rows]="rows" />
}
```

```html
@browser {
  <app-map-widget [location]="location" />
}
```

This would help with:
- rendering static/SEO-friendly content on the server;
- rendering browser-only widgets that depend on DOM APIs such as window, document, ResizeObserver, canvas, maps, charts, etc.;
- replacing SSR-only markup with an interactive browser implementation;
- reducing isPlatformBrowser / PLATFORM_ID boilerplate in components;
- avoiding accidental SSR execution of browser-only template branches;
- making hydration differences intentional instead of accidental.

### Proposed solution

```
@server {
  <p>This content is rendered during SSR/prerendering only.</p>
}

@browser {
  <p>This content is rendered in the browser only.</p>
}
```

#### Possible semantics:

1. `@server` is rendered during SSR and prerendering.
2. `@server` is skipped or removed during browser rendering/hydration in a framework-defined way.
3. `@browser` is not emitted into the server HTML.
4. `@browser` is rendered only after the app runs in the browser.
5. Both blocks should be hydration-aware, so Angular does not treat the intentional DOM difference as a hydration mismatch.
6. Ideally, expressions/components inside `@browser` should not be evaluated on the server, and expressions/components inside `@server` should not be evaluated in the browser.

A possible future enhancement, if technically feasible, would be allowing server-only branches to be excluded from the browser bundle and browser-only branches from the server bundle. However, the main request is about template semantics and hydration correctness.

#### Why not just use `@if (isBrowser)`?

Current workaround:

```ts
readonly isBrowser = isPlatformBrowser(inject(PLATFORM_ID));
```

```html
@if (isBrowser) {
  <app-browser-only-widget />
}
```

#### This works for simple cases, but has drawbacks:

- every component needs its own platform guard;
- it hides an SSR/hydration concern inside component class code;
custom directives can vary across projects;
- it is easy to accidentally create server/client DOM mismatches;
- it is not obvious to readers that the branch has platform-level rendering semantics;
- it does not provide an official hydration-aware contract.


#### Why not `@defer`?

`@defer` is about when to load/render a block.

This feature would be about where a block is allowed to render: server, browser, or potentially both.

For example, a map/chart/browser-widget should not merely be deferred. In many SSR apps it should be explicitly browser-only.

### Alternatives considered

The exact syntax is open to discussion. For example:

```html
@platform ('server') {
  ...
}

@platform ('browser') {
  ...
}
```

or

```html
@render (server) {
  ...
}

@render (browser) {
  ...
}
```

However, `@server` and `@browser` are short, readable, and consistent with the new control-flow style.

#### Additional considerations

- How should `@server` behave after hydration: remove, ignore, preserve until replacement, or support different strategies?
- Should adjacent `@server` + `@browser` blocks be treated as an explicit replacement pair?
- Should this work the same way for SSR and prerender/SSG?
- Should there be a diagnostic if `@server` or `@browser` creates invalid HTML structure around hydration markers?
- How should this interact with incremental/partial hydration features?

I think a first-class primitive here would make Angular SSR templates easier to read and less error-prone.

